msgid "Record Keeping"
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:29
msgid ""
"You have the ability to use Google Drive with your ``pyladies.com`` "
"account (please don't polute your personal Google drive!).  Just log into"
" `drive.google.com`_ with your PyLadies email login information.  With "
"that,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:31
msgid ""
"Create a form (e.g. with Google Forms) that allows someone to report the "
"incident online.  See :ref:`receiving` for what details to collect.  An "
"example form can be found `here`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:32
msgid ""
"Publish the form within your location's page (e.g. local Meetup page, "
"website, Facebook) as well as emailed out when it initially is published."
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:33
msgid ""
"Publish contact information (e.g. your location's email) in case they "
"wish to not fill out the form or want talk to someone directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:34
msgid ""
"Set up `email notifications`_ for any form response so you don't miss "
"anything"
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:35
msgid ""
"Create documents for any notes that you/the organizers take, write down "
"any actions took and the resolve, any email conversations.  Anything that"
" is done in relation to the incident should be documented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:36
msgid ""
"It may be a good setup to create folders per incident.  Then you can just"
" upload PDF printouts of email conversations, or quickly write notes "
"about conversations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:38
msgid "The purpose of maintaining a \"paper trail\" is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:40
msgid ""
"If you step down as an organizer, or another organizer receives a "
"complaint regarding a previous offender, it can be dealt with in a more "
"appropriate manner, and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:41
msgid "Maintain a record in case local authorities ever get involved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:44
msgid "Informing PyLadies Global"
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:46
msgid ""
"If an incident happens in your local PyLadies community, you must report "
"it to the global organization via `our CoC reporting form`_.  The purpose"
" is very similar to :ref:`record` - for the global organization to be "
"aware of what's going on in case of any legal or PR action is "
"needed/taken, as well as look for a pattern of behavior (e.g. a repeat "
"harasser moves locations, if a community is particularly unwelcoming and "
"may need more help)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:48
msgid ""
"You are of course welcome and invited to request help from the global "
"PyLadies organization.  We are here for resources, advice, or just to "
"talk to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:50
msgid ""
"The global organization is also responsible for complaints of local "
"organizers.  If you received or witnessed unwanted behavior in any way "
"that breaks our :ref:`coc` by another organizer, please do not hesitate "
"to contact us.  You may report any violations via `our global report "
"form`_, or contact us at `coc@pyladies.com`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:52
msgid "The following people maintain any :ref:`coc` reports:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:54
msgid "Esther Nam (`la@pyladies.com`_)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../organizer/difficult/responding.rst:55
msgid "Lynn Root (`sf@pyladies.com`_)"
